,"Blocks intestinal cholesterol absorption","Activates peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor alpha"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFibrates work primarily by \u003Cstrong\u003Eactivating peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor alpha (PPAR-alpha)\u003C/strong\u003E. This nuclear receptor activation leads to increased lipoprotein lipase activity, enhanced fatty acid oxidation, and reduced hepatic triglyceride synthesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases bile acid excretion\u003C/strong\u003E: this describes the mechanism of bile acid sequestrants, which bind bile acids in the intestine to reduce cholesterol levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks intestinal cholesterol absorption\u003C/strong\u003E: this describes the mechanism of ezetimibe, which inhibits the Niemann-Pick C1-Like 1 protein to prevent cholesterol absorption.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits hydroxymethylglutaryl-CoA reductase\u003C/strong\u003E: this describes the mechanism of statins, which reduce cholesterol synthesis in the liver.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits cholesteryl ester transfer protein\u003C/strong\u003E: this describes the mechanism of CETP inhibitors, which increase HDL cholesterol levels by preventing cholesteryl ester transfer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThrough PPAR-alpha activation, fibrates effectively reduce triglycerides by 30-50% and increase HDL cholesterol by 10-20%. They are particularly useful in treating hypertriglyceridaemia and mixed dyslipidaemia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fibrates reduce triglycerides and increase HDL cholesterol primarily by activating peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor alpha (PPAR-alpha).","PPAR-alpha activation increases lipoprotein lipase activity and fatty acid oxidation while decreasing hepatic triglyceride synthesis.","Fibrates are particularly effective in treating hypertriglyceridaemia and mixed dyslipidaemia."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67387"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16838"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67387","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67387"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-28T17:23:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-28T17:24:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9528"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82189"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji